	<p>Three colors of Labrador are known: classic black, fawn (from light cream, almost white to brightly red - red-fox) and chocolate (from light brown to the color of dark chocolate). Labradors have the following rule of color inheritance: black color is dominant, and fawn and chocolate are recessive, that is, to get puppies of one of the recessive colors, both parents must be recessive, or one of the parents must have a recessive color, or both parents with different color, must carry the same recessive gene.</p>
	</div>
</div><br>

<p> Nature carries the material connection between generations with the help of genes. Genes are parts of the DNA molecule that is part of the chromosomes. Dogs have thirty-nine pairs of chromosomes, thirty-eight of them are autosomes (non-sex chromosomes) and one pair of sex chromosomes. Each organism has two genes that influence the development of a particular trait, since each autosome is present in two copies, and one of them is obtained from the mother, the other from the father. </p>
<p> Two genes occupying the same position (or locus) in paired (homologous) chromosomes are called alleles. </p>
<p> Alleles are alternative states of the same gene. If an individual has two identical alleles, which determines any sign, it is called homozygous. If the alleles in one locus are different, it is accepted to call the animal heterozygous, or carrier of the recessive gene. Simple Mendelian traits (traits controlled by a single gene) can be divided into dominant and recessive. If the presence of a single allele of a gene is sufficient for the manifestation of a trait, such a trait is called dominant. The allele that conditions this trait is also referred to as dominant and is designated by capital letter. If the manifestation of a trait requires the presence of two identical alleles of a gene, this trait is called recessive. Recessive gene is designated by lowercase letter. Two sets of genes control the color of Labrador. One set of genes is responsible for whether the Labrador will be dark (black or chocolate) or light (yellow). </p>
<p> Dark is dominant over light. Thus, a Labrador whose genotype is EE (dominant homozygous) or Her (heterozygous) will be dark; Only Labradors that are her (homozygous recessive) can be bright. The second set of genes comes into play only if the Labrador is dark (or EE, or Her). This set is responsible for whether the Labrador will be black (dominant type) or chocolate (recessive type). Thus, a dark dog (i.e., EE / Her), which is BB (dominant homozygous) or Bb (heterozygous), will be black, while the only way a dog can become chocolate is to be dark (EE / Her) and bb (homozygous recessive). Thus, opportunities for blacks are EEBB, EEBb, EeBB, or EeBb. Opportunities for fawn dogs - eeBB, opportunities for chocolate dogs - EEbb or Eebb. Remember that puppies will take one E / e from a bitch and one from a dog, as well as one B / b from a bitch and one from a dog, which will be their full set. If you had two parents who were both EeBb (externally black), you can get all three colors in the litter! Moreover, when you realize that a pair of fawn can give their puppies only a combination of it, you realize why two fawn produce only yellow ones. </p>
<p> Similarly, two chocolate dogs can only give their bb puppies, so two chocolates can never produce a black puppy. The combination of eebb is an interesting case, as it is a fawn dog with chocolate pigmentation on the nose and eyelids. In the ring, such a dog may be disqualified. A dog that is bb always has a chocolate or so-called "liver" pigment.</p>
